subSubSection.paragraph:
Diagnosis.
The face and lunule (
Fig. 2B
) are silvery-grey pruinose. The postpronotum (
Fig. 2A
) has 1 to several long setulae (longer than the setulae on the scutum) medially from the postpronotal seta. In the male (see figs 8–16, 19 in 
McAlpine & Tanasijtshuk 1972
), the epandrial complex is simple, small, and yellowish- to silvery-grey pruinose, with no central epandrial process; the surstylar lobe is short and slender, the phallus (
Fig. 3A
) is broad in lateral view with a wedge-shaped anterobasal process at a 90° angle from the thin elongate pointed process. In the female (
Figs 3D–E
), tergites (
Fig. 3E
) with tergite 6 enlarged and slightly less than 2 X wider than long, tergite 7 present and strap-like, tergite 8 longer than wide, slightly tapering distally; sternites (
Fig. 3D
) with sternite 6 enlarged and about 2 X wider than long, sternite 7 present and arcuate.
